Definition 7.1. Inverse categories An inverse category is a category ${\mathcal{C}}$ where every arrow $f\in{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)$ has a unique generalised inverse $f^{\ddagger}\in{\mathcal{C}}(Y,X)$ satisfying $ff^{\ddagger}f=f$ and $f^{\ddagger}ff^{\ddagger}=f^{\ddagger}$. A single-object inverse category is called an inverse monoid.
